results.description: I believe these are twining vines. I researched online saying that tendril and twining vines need to secure slender poles or wire to the fence for the twines and tendrils to grasp onto. This is seen here. Without the support, the vines will eventually end up clinging to themselves and create huge knots and tangles, which also looks apparent too.

comments.body:
I usually remove this plant and try to replace it with the native Virginia creeper, which is a very similar plant. I do see more insects eating the Virginia creeper, which may keep its growth in check more, but also, it is more integrated into the ecosystem that way, supporting the food web.

Here in north America, it is an invasive plant, but it's not one of the worst ones because it rarely strays very far from urban areas.

I'm not aware of it killing trees though. More often, this species seems likely to climb exposed surfaces. Virginia creeper is the one I more often see draped over trees, but even there, it doesn't usually seem to kill trees the way some of the more "strangly" vines like grape, porcelain berry, or kudzu do.
Thanks. Will it kill the tree?
Not usually, but look up to the top of the tree when there are leaves. If there is nearly as much ivy as tree then you have a problem.
